Present law authorizes the secretary of the Dept. of Culture, Recreation and Tourism to
appoint competent men to serve as police officers in local parks.
Present law authorizes state park wardens to enforce all rules and regulations of the Dept.
of Culture, Recreation and Tourism, office of state parks, and all laws of the state of La.
within their jurisdiction.
Proposed law retains present law and authorizes the secretary of the Dept. of Culture,
Recreation and Tourism to appoint veterans honorably discharged to serve as state park
wardens.
Proposed law defines "veteran" as an honorably discharged former or current member of
the U.S. Armed Forces or organized militia of the several states and territories, including but
not limited to a member of the Army, Navy, Air Force, Space Force, Marine Corps, Coast
Guard, Natl. Guard, Air Natl. Guard, Reserves, State Guard, or a commissioned officer of
the Public Health Service, Environmental Science Services Admin., or Natl. Oceanic and
Atmospheric Admin.
Proposed law provides that if the veteran is employed by either a municipality, local
governing authority, or office of state parks, the veteran must meet all training requirements
and qualifications for employment.
Proposed law requires the veteran to be certified by the Council on Peace Officer Standards
and Training (P.O.S.T.) or be qualified by P.O.S.T.
(Amends R.S. 33:4558 and R.S. 56:1688(A))
Summary of Amendments Adopted by House
The Committee Amendments Proposed by House Committee on Judiciary to the original
bill:
1. Provide that the veteran is an honorably discharged former member of the
military.
2. Provide that a veteran employed by a municipality, local governing authority, or
office of state parks, the veteran must meet all training requirements and
qualifications for employment.
3. Require a veteran provided for in proposed law to be certified by the Council on
Peace Officer Standards and Training (P.O.S.T.) or be qualified by P.O.S.T.
